INSERT INTO Tasks (TaskID, CompanyName, date_started, date_finished, details, header, Staff, Bug) VALUES (2317, 'Eastbourne General District Hospital', '2000-09-22 00:00:00', '2000-10-02 00:00:00', 'call logged by John sinstadt. No backup for Thursay SOMETHING happened 2pm which upset system resulting in either powercut or someone turning machine off without shuting databases first. Hense all data after that time corrupted beyond resonble time for repair will have to go back to Wednesday\'s backup.  John asked if he could manually changes docket numbers so doesn\'t have dulpicates, told him no changing of data manually allowed, will print dummy dockert and fill in information as old ones come back in. call closed.WW Mon 25/09/2000 - Phoned again today to say that the server crashed on Friday with a PANIC trap error. Lawrie has disabled the system audit mechanism. I have told them that we need the PANIC trap error number to do anything. They are getting back to me. Will be checking there backup tommorow, may well need fixing if corruption exists.WW Tues 26/09/2000 - They still have corruption on there live database. Dropped and remade hrs_wrkd, and cw_dets tables. I also took data.train and data.future out of the backup loop. This stops them from being opened each night after backup. They are not used much so a manual backup every so often should be fine. This will save them from being corrupted if the server goes down, as they will be shut and safe. Will check the backup tonight for further corruption. There was further corruption in the cw_job file, as John still could not raise a fault job. I rebuilt the table and created a test job (job id 15692) which saved OK. Waiting to here back from John.WW - Mon 2nd October 2000 - Still not heard back, assuming everything is OK.WW - Wed 18th October 2000 - The panic trap happened again and caused another crash. He noted the panic trap this time;AUDIT: Error on collection file write - 28AUDIT: Warning: low free block count on audit deviceAUDIT: Free block count below threshold.AUDIT: Out of alternate directoriesAUDIT: Subsystem termination due to unrecoverable error.PANIC: k_trap  - kernel mode trap type 0x0000000EThe problem was with the audit system, It has now been disabled as was not really needed. Non of our other sites use it, and it is OFF by default. A system integrity check was run, to get rid of the corruption in their audit files which was causing the audit system to panic trap whenevr it tried to write to them. The system is working fine now. Also there was no corruption of the live database this time.', 'Trying to save docket in helpdesk and error message unable to acces control file.', 'Kate Hamilton', 0);
INSERT INTO Tasks (TaskID, CompanyName, date_started, date_finished, details, header, Staff, Bug) VALUES (2318, 'Royal Dundee Liff Hospital', '2000-09-25 00:00:00', '2000-09-26 00:00:00', 'I got Glenys to run a project details report. It seems that the commitment is against an order which was lost when they had a disc crash and corruption. I might be able to delete the fx_dets record, and adjust the budget? That is if the budget is wrong as well? Apparently the budget is OK as this year it is a different budget from last year, and they don\'t mind that last years budget is wrong.Projects and order numbers;Project: ES001    Order: 2048600 - for 4450Project: SM004N    Order: 2050700 - for 3540WW - Tues 26/09/2000 - The orders appear not to be in the database, but the pj_dets commitment field is picking them up? Although there is a record in fx_dets, this is not used in the commitment calculation, so the orders must still be in the system. My guess is that the order headers (oh_dets) for the orders have been lost, but the order lines (ol_dets) are still there. If so I will have to remove these as well. I was right. I have now deleted the fx_dets records (but there was no real need as these weren\'t being referenced, but I did them any way just in case), and the headerless orderlines, and the pj_dets are now showing the correct total commitment.', 'There pj_dets screen is still showing commitment even though there are no outstanding orders.', 'William Wragg', 0);
INSERT INTO Tasks (TaskID, CompanyName, date_started, date_finished, details, header, Staff, Bug) VALUES (2319, 'Royal Hampshire County Hospital', '2000-09-25 00:00:00', '2000-10-03 00:00:00', 'The tables he requires are:For jobs still open - hrs_wrkdFor closed jobs - cc_phistI have done a quick crystal report selecting the fields - activity_code, date_recorded, docket_number, and hours.Then I hid drill down on the detail section, to stop all the records being shown (he only wants the sub totals). I then inserted a subtotal on the hours field, grouped by activity code. I then added a subtotal on the docket_number field (a distinct count - must be distinct so that it doesn\'t include multiple occurences of the same docket no.), grouped again by activity code. The select criteria are then set for a specific week, and the reportproduces something like:Activity code                                                     No. of Jobs       No. of Hours                Hours/JobsWORK                                                                      5                      45.0                             9.0DAY5                                                                        1                        7.5                             7.5The Hours/Jobs field is an Formula field dividing on subtotal with the other. Waiting to here back from Roger. Only mentioned to him about which tables, and hours subtotal, along with the hiding of the drill down.WW Tues 26/09/2000 - Roger is speaking to Bob about how to implement the report in crystal reports.KH 031000 - According to MB BL sorted out Roger\'s problem. Call closed.', 'Roger wishes to do a report on hours worked for a given week, grouped (and sub totaled) by activity code.', 'William Wragg', 0);
