INSERT INTO Tasks (TaskID, CompanyName, date_started, date_finished, details, header, Staff, Bug) VALUES (2545, 'Perth Royal Infirmary', '2001-03-15 00:00:00', '2001-03-19 00:00:00', 'Call logged by James Young.Dialed on. Not much space. Half done processes mean will have to restore. Cleared down /u1/tmp and printfiles.  Delete data. Apparently error occurred yesterday afternoon so Wednesdays backup is no good. Restore from Tuesdays backup. Had to delete aclenv.3.50 for space. Has 121meg but need 100meg as buffer. James said will talk with his people about getting a bigger disc.  In the mean time James asked for indtruction s on clearing down file as he said was not aware that was required. Email sent giving instructions on clearing down /u1/tmp and printfiles. Call closed.WW - Fri. 16/03/2001 - The problem stems from the fact that although the vostats command shows that there is approx. 53MB allocated space available, there is infact non. If you run the suspect insert command in sql, it comes back with the dbms_status$() error for the cryptic status$() error. In this case it came back with \'No segmanets in volume/database. (-702)\'. The problem now is that to dump all the data will be a problem as there may not be enough space available. This is the corse that we are going to take;1) make a maksysb.2) allocate all the space available to the /u1 filesystem.3) kick off the dbdump.4) When dbdump finished backup the dump directory onto a tape.5) delete the old database, after moving out the dumped data.6) recreate the database with 800~850MB volume, or if enough space with the multivolume database system.7) dbload the data into the new database8) run \'disc $PHABASE/lib/source.dis\'9) shutdown the database and delete the dump directory.10) do a backup of the whole of /u111) delete the /u1 file system.12) recreate the /u1 file system with 1503232kb13) reload the /u1 file system backed up in step 10)14) at some near future date add a new disk drive.MB - 16/3/01 mksysbb taken MB - 17/3/01 allocated \"spare\" space to u1 for dbdumpstarted at 07:50 completed 08:40 no errorsMB - 19/3/01 logged on found root full, removed core and smit logs.08:50 Scott changed tapes so proceeded with manual backup of u1 (find u1 -print | cpio -oBvc >/dev/rmt0)Proceding to recreate database and load data.KH/WW 190301 - Dialed in. Moved dumped db to $PHABASE and deleted data. Created new database and started dbload at 10:12am.  11.12am dialed in to check progress fx_dets was loading. 12.12pm dialed in ph_hist loading df -sk revealed 78% used 375988 free.13.23pm dialed in to check progress. Df -sk revealed 84% used 268008 free.2.30pm dbload completed. Check subs dilelooked good. Removed dumpfile. In root find u1 -print | cpio -oBvc > /dev/rmt0. Readback looks ok. MC reallocating space. Database looks good. Re Scot nologin to remian on to inhibit users logging in so that good backup is guaranteed. Scot will put new/mondays tape in.  Will removed nologin first thing tomorrow morning. Call closed.KH 200301 - Dialed in on the off chance that modem still on, which it was, to check last nights backup.  Failed to write anything, according to WW missing up to date in BINDIR, sent update programs down the modem.  According to James no one checks the backup.  Ran manual backup and repaire overloaded tabel ph_w_don, then left messgae for James that can go back on.  Email sent to James and Donald Marshall confirming system up and runnig again and Stressing the inportance that the backups are checked daily.  General Pharaoh program management document attched with e-mail containaing instruction to check backups. Call closed.', 'db insert into ph_w_don status = -99', 'Kate Hamilton', 0);
