INSERT INTO Tasks (TaskID, CompanyName, date_started, date_finished, details, header, Staff, Bug) VALUES (2877, 'Barts and London NHS Trust', '2002-02-06 00:00:00', '2002-02-07 00:00:00', 'For example on Friday 14 Dec. 2001 they started at 21:12 and finished at 06:40 however on Friday 1 Feb. 2002 they started at 21:22 and finished at 09:08 a difference of 2 hours and 18 minutes. I was wondering if this might be as a result of additional checks you may have put in place as a result of the date problem my colleague Phil Turner was having when transferring records to history recently. If so can we revert to the original check routine, if not could you let me know why it is now taking so long to run the diagnostic check.WW - Wed. 06/02/2002 - The increased time is due to the single volume I but in on 21/01/2002. I have put some time info printouts in the $BINDIR/diags to see which takes the increased time. I will check on them tomorrow morning and decide what to do.WW - Thu. 07/02/2002 - I checked the timeings and decided to do the following;Check Volumes everyday, Check Indexes everyday except Thursday, Check tables only on Thursdays. I used the following code in the $BINDIR/diags script to acheive this;TMPWKDAY=`date +%w`# Check evrydayecho \"Carrying out volume check   `date +\'%H:%M\'`\"$ACLDIR/diag/volchk        > $TMPFILE  2>&1# Check only on Thursdaysif [ $TMPWKDAY -eq 4 ]then    echo \"Carrying out table check    `date +\'%H:%M\'`\"    $ACLDIR/diag/tblchk -Oallow_syncs -Oall >> $TMPFILE  2>&1fi# Check everyday except Thursdaysif [ $TMPWKDAY -ne 4 ]then    echo \"Carrying out index check    `date +\'%H:%M\'`\"    $ACLDIR/diag/idxchk       >> $TMPFILE  2>&1fiWhen we do their 3.7 update we will rebuild their database back into a multi-volume one. This should speed up the diags abck to their original times.', 'Phil has noticed the nightly diagnostic checks are taking considerably longer than they were previously.', 'William Wragg', 0);
